<DOC><DOCNO> AP880902-0104 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1053EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-TropicalWeather     09-02 0186</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Tropical Weather,0190</SECOND><HEAD>New Tropical Storm Develops Off Mexico</HEAD><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A weather system in the Gulf of Mexico strengthenedtoday into tropical storm Debby and was expected to bring up to 10inches of rain to parts of Mexico.   The Mexican government posted storm warnings from Santa Cruz toVera Cruz for Debby, which had maximum sustained wind of 40 mph,with gusts up to 50 mph, said National Hurricane Center forecasterHal Gerrish.   At 8 a.m. EDT, Debby was 180 miles southeast of Tampico, Mexico,moving west at 8 mph.   ``Locally heavy rains up to 10 inches can be expected overportions of Mexico,'' Gerrish said. ``Some flash floods and mudslides may occur in the warned area and inland today and tonight.''   The storm, designated a tropical storm and named Debby when itssustained wind passed the minimum 39 mph, was expected to weakenand die out soon after hitting the coast.   Debby is the fourth named storm of the 1988 Atlantic hurricaneseason. None have reached the 74 mph wind speed at which a storm isclassified as a hurricane.</TEXT></DOC>